00:15:46,769 --> 00:15:49,488
It wasn't funny.
It soaked through Gramoo's Oriental.

240
00:15:49,569 --> 00:15:51,924
There's still a big spot on the floor.

241
00:15:54,969 --> 00:15:57,847
Okay. We need wallpaper paste.
Hey, Cece.

242
00:15:58,409 --> 00:16:00,479
Isn't there anything else you remember?

243
00:16:00,849 --> 00:16:03,204
How did you propose? Was it romantic?

244
00:16:03,769 --> 00:16:06,966
I kinda just blurted it out
over a root beer float.

245
00:16:07,049 --> 00:16:08,926
Root beer float, that sounds good.

246
00:16:09,649 --> 00:16:14,404
Did she mention any contest that she won?
I mean, she must have had some awards.

247
00:16:14,529 --> 00:16:16,042
She was so talented and all.

248
00:16:16,209 --> 00:16:17,528
She was talented.

249
00:16:17,809 --> 00:16:20,004
Honey, I wish I could help you a little more.

250
00:16:20,089 --> 00:16:23,240
It's just that your mother and I
had kind of a whirlwind courtship.

251
00:16:23,329 --> 00:16:25,479
She came to town
with a travelling theatre group.

252
00:16:25,569 --> 00:16:28,527
I proposed on our second date,
two weeks later we were married.

253
00:16:28,609 --> 00:16:31,442
Almost nine months later,
you were here and she was gone.

254
00:16:31,529 --> 00:16:34,327
- Was it a nice funeral?
- Yes. Lovely funeral.

255
00:16:34,689 --> 00:16:36,725
Grenaldi Brothers did a beautiful job.

256
00:16:36,809 --> 00:16:39,846
Lots of pink roses,
and I used the white hearse.

257
00:16:40,049 --> 00:16:43,086
How about this flowered wallpaper
for your room?

258
00:16:45,249 --> 00:16:46,728
How about this?

259
00:16:50,649 --> 00:16:53,038
- Hi, Mr. Owett.
- Hey, Veda.

260
00:16:55,049 --> 00:16:57,438
- How's your report coming?
- Great.

261
00:16:57,929 --> 00:17:00,762
I have so much to say,
I hardly know where to start.

262
00:17:00,849 --> 00:17:05,047
I've been rereading Virginia Woolf.
I think she'd be a natural for you.

263
00:17:05,729 --> 00:17:07,208
She led a fascinating life.

264
00:17:07,969 --> 00:17:10,244
Thanks, but I think
I'm gonna stick to my mum.

265
00:17:10,329 --> 00:17:12,206
She led a fascinating life, too.

266
00:17:13,329 --> 00:17:14,967
I'm sure she did.

267
00:17:18,849 --> 00:17:22,478
He was giving you an easy out so you
didn't have to write about your mother.

268
00:17:22,569 --> 00:17:24,048
But I want to write about her.

269
00:17:24,129 --> 00:17:26,245
You're crazy.
What was her big achievement?

270
00:17:26,329 --> 00:17:29,241
- Did she invent gravity?
- No one invented gravity.

271
00:17:29,809 --> 00:17:30,924
It just exists.

272
00:17:31,009 --> 00:17:32,203
Then what did she do?

273
00:17:32,289 --> 00:17:34,359
Well, I'm not supposed to talk about it...

274
00:17:34,449 --> 00:17:37,600
...but since I'm going to write about it,
I might as well tell you.

275
00:17:37,689 --> 00:17:39,486
She was a spy against the Russians.

276
00:17:39,569 --> 00:17:42,037
Please. Who do you think you're kidding?

277
00:17:42,129 --> 00:17:44,199
And where did she spy
on the Russians from?

278
00:17:44,289 --> 00:17:45,517
Here in Pennsylvania?

279
00:17:45,609 --> 00:17:47,804
No, not here in Pennsylvania.

280
00:17:48,169 --> 00:17:50,808
She went to Russia undercover
with her acting troupe...

281
00:17:50,889 --> 00:17:54,279
...and got a lot of highly sensitive
secret plans sent back.

282
00:17:55,089 --> 00:17:58,764
Just when she was about to go home,
she got caught and they killed her.

283
00:17:58,849 --> 00:18:01,602
So, when did she have you
between all of her acting...

284
00:18:01,689 --> 00:18:03,566
...and spying and getting caught?

285
00:18:03,649 --> 00:18:04,877
That's simple.

286
00:18:05,169 --> 00:18:08,605
She was pregnant with me
when she went to Russia, but didn't know.

287
00:18:08,769 --> 00:18:11,329
When the Russians found out,
they waited to shoot her.

288
00:18:11,409 --> 00:18:14,481
You're not allowed to kill pregnant women
anywhere in the world.

289
00:18:14,569 --> 00:18:16,764
So she had you in jail in Russia?

290
00:18:17,529 --> 00:18:20,646
Well, actually, I was born in Siberia
and then they shot her...

291
00:18:20,729 --> 00:18:22,685
...and sent me home to my dad.

292
00:18:22,769 --> 00:18:26,205
If bullshit wore a bra, you'd be top-heavy.

293
00:18:26,609 --> 00:18:27,598
Come on, Judy.

294
00:18:29,889 --> 00:18:31,845
Ask anyone. Ask my dad.

295
00:18:33,529 --> 00:18:35,167
It could be true.

296
00:18:44,529 --> 00:18:47,362
<i>How come guys talk so much</i>
<i>when they have nothing to say...</i>

297
00:18:47,449 --> 00:18:50,043
<i>... and girls have plenty to say,</i>
<i>but no one'll listen?</i>

298
00:18:57,369 --> 00:19:00,759
I used to come down here
and sleep on this spot when I was little.

299
00:19:04,609 --> 00:19:06,679
My report's gonna be a disaster.

300
00:19:07,169 --> 00:19:09,842
Everything I know about her
fits into one little box.

301
00:19:10,569 --> 00:19:11,718
A box?

302
00:19:15,609 --> 00:19:18,487
Oh, Vada, what a sweet baby book!

303
00:19:20,849 --> 00:19:23,238
It's only filled out to page two.

304
00:19:25,889 --> 00:19:28,198
I was eight pounds, four ounces.

305
00:19:28,369 --> 00:19:29,927
There are so many programmes.

306
00:19:30,329 --> 00:19:31,887
She was in a lot of plays.

307
00:19:33,169 --> 00:19:35,125
Dad said that when she was on stage...

308
00:19:35,369 --> 00:19:37,883
...she held the audience
in the palm of her hand.

309
00:19:39,649 --> 00:19:42,686
What's this? "December 8, 1958."

310
00:19:43,289 --> 00:19:45,519
I don't know. Dad doesn't either.

311
00:19:45,969 --> 00:19:48,005
Well, it must mean something.

312
00:19:48,449 --> 00:19:50,326
She was obviously very sentimental.

313
00:19:51,169 --> 00:19:53,763
This, that's one of my favourite things,
her passport.

314
00:19:56,049 --> 00:19:58,040
Vada, she's so beautiful.

315
00:20:00,809 --> 00:20:04,085
"Margaret Ann Muldovan,
born in Los Angeles, California...

316
00:20:04,169 --> 00:20:07,047
"...February 7, 1936." Aquarius.

317
00:20:07,409 --> 00:20:10,446
Margaret's my middle name,
but everybody called her Maggie.

318
00:20:11,049 --> 00:20:13,722
- Los Angeles. Have you ever been there?
- No.

319
00:20:14,729 --> 00:20:17,402
You know, they say that it never rains...

320
00:20:17,929 --> 00:20:20,602
...that you can barbecue on Christmas Day.

321
00:20:21,609 --> 00:20:25,045
Instead of riding your bike,
you just surf over to your friend's house.

322
00:20:25,129 --> 00:20:27,279
The place is just crawling with celebrities.

323
00:20:27,369 --> 00:20:30,679
I know someone who saw Walter Matthau
picking up his dry cleaning.

324
00:20:30,769 --> 00:20:32,725
Is that why Uncle Phil moved there?

325
00:20:32,969 --> 00:20:35,085
Uncle Phil just needed a change.

326
00:20:35,449 --> 00:20:37,167
A little adventure.

327
00:20:38,209 --> 00:20:41,167
I wonder why she got a passport
if she never went anywhere?

328
00:20:41,249 --> 00:20:42,921
Well, you've gotta be prepared.

329
00:20:43,329 --> 00:20:45,206
I'm definitely travelling some day.

330
00:20:46,969 --> 00:20:48,368
Why not now?

331
00:20:49,329 --> 00:20:50,603
What do you mean?

332
00:20:51,169 --> 00:20:54,081
How would you like to visit
your Uncle Phil in Los Angeles...

333
00:20:54,169 --> 00:20:58,606
...next week, during your spring vacation?
You could do research on your mum.

334
00:20:59,009 --> 00:21:01,204
But what about you and the baby?
You need me.

335
00:21:01,809 --> 00:21:04,960
But I'm not due to have the baby
for another six weeks or so.

336
00:21:06,409 --> 00:21:08,365
It would be kind of great.

337
00:21:08,449 --> 00:21:10,280
It would be fantastic!

338
00:21:11,129 --> 00:21:13,006
But Dad will never go for it.

339
00:21:14,049 --> 00:21:15,926
You leave your father to me.

340
00:21:16,009 --> 00:21:18,204
You should encourage her
to spread her wings.

341
00:21:18,289 --> 00:21:20,484
She can spread her wings
here in Pennsylvania.

342
00:21:20,569 --> 00:21:22,287
You don't send a child to Los Angeles.

343
00:21:22,369 --> 00:21:25,088
She could come back with her ears pierced
and legs shaved.

344
00:21:25,169 --> 00:21:27,205
She's not a child. She's a young woman.

345
00:21:27,289 --> 00:21:29,007
- She's on the brink of...
- Disaster.

346
00:21:29,089 --> 00:21:32,399
- Disaster lurks behind every palm tree.
- You're being narrow-minded.

347
00:21:32,489 --> 00:21:35,720
Maybe when she's a little older,
I'd be more than happy to bring...

348
00:21:35,809 --> 00:21:37,845
Hi, Vada. We were just having a little...

349
00:21:37,969 --> 00:21:39,880
You were just having a fight about me.

350
00:21:39,969 --> 00:21:41,880
Wouldn't you like to hear my opinion?

351
00:21:42,889 --> 00:21:43,878
Of course.

352
00:21:43,969 --> 00:21:46,529
I think that if I'm old enough
to accept a new baby...

353
00:21:46,609 --> 00:21:48,679
...and old enough to accept a new room...

354
00:21:48,769 --> 00:21:50,248
...I'm old enough for California.

355
00:21:50,329 --> 00:21:52,718
I know it's fun to think about these things,
but...

356
00:21:52,809 --> 00:21:54,162
I already bought a ticket.

357
00:21:54,249 --> 00:21:57,559
- What?
- I used my money and got a great deal.

358
00:21:57,649 --> 00:21:59,958
It's a Q47-NR five-day fare...

359
00:22:00,049 --> 00:22:03,644
...which means I'll change planes
in Dallas and stay over a Saturday.

360
00:22:03,729 --> 00:22:06,801
There's no exchanges or refunds,
so if you don't let me go...

361
00:22:06,929 --> 00:22:09,807
...then I will have wasted
my entire life savings.

362
00:22:14,769 --> 00:22:17,966
Isn't it against the law
to sell airline tickets to minors?

363
00:22:21,209 --> 00:22:24,042
Don't tell me you aided and abetted
this little scheme?

364
00:22:24,129 --> 00:22:25,642
Vada needed me.

365
00:22:25,929 --> 00:22:28,284
The airline requires
the signature of an adult.

366
00:22:28,369 --> 00:22:31,281
They forgot to ask for one
who wasn't having hormone surges.

367
00:22:31,369 --> 00:22:35,123
Come on, Harry!
We're talking about five days here.

368
00:22:35,209 --> 00:22:38,121
We're going overboard
for just a simple school assignment.

369
00:22:38,209 --> 00:22:40,165
<i>It's not a little school assignment.</i>

370
00:22:40,249 --> 00:22:42,809
<i>I think maybe all of this</i>
<i>is happening for a reason.</i>

371
00:22:43,169 --> 00:22:44,921
<i>Reason? What reason? What?</i>

372
00:22:45,009 --> 00:22:49,048
<i>Phil's moving to LA, Gramoo's passing.</i>
<i>The baby being born.</i>

373
00:22:49,289 --> 00:22:50,722
<i>Vada's report.</i>

374
00:22:50,809 --> 00:22:55,803
Maybe all of these are signs. Signs that
it's time for Vada to take this trip.

375
00:22:56,609 --> 00:22:57,758
Signs?

376
00:22:58,849 --> 00:23:01,124
Let me get the Loch Ness Monster
on the phone.

377
00:23:01,209 --> 00:23:02,961
You two have a lot to talk about.

378
00:23:03,049 --> 00:23:05,483
No, I'm sorry.
Vada is not going to Los Angeles.

379
00:23:05,569 --> 00:23:08,402
Now, I have made my decision,
and that is final.

380
00:23:08,569 --> 00:23:10,366
And remember, don't talk to anyone.

381
00:23:10,449 --> 00:23:12,963
Even if a nun sits next to you,
don't talk to her.

382
00:23:13,049 --> 00:23:14,368
No nuns. Got it.

383
00:23:14,489 --> 00:23:16,445
And no boys. Promise me.

384
00:23:16,889 --> 00:23:20,279
Those LA people are all so corrupt,
you'll end up pregnant and on drugs.

385
00:23:20,369 --> 00:23:23,167
Don't run to me when you're in the morgue
with a toe tag...

386
00:23:23,249 --> 00:23:26,161
...having been beaten to
an unrecognisable pulp by a surfer.

387
00:23:26,249 --> 00:23:27,762
And don't make eye contact.

388
00:23:27,969 --> 00:23:30,563
It communicates an implied vulnerability.

389
00:23:30,649 --> 00:23:32,002
What does that mean?

390
00:23:32,209 --> 00:23:35,167
It means I'm a paranoid nitwit
who's never let his baby girl...

391
00:23:35,249 --> 00:23:38,286
...out of his sight for the simple reason
he's a paranoid nitwit.

392
00:23:38,769 --> 00:23:42,444
So, why don't you just say, "Oh, Dad,"
and get on the damn plane already.

393
00:23:42,529 --> 00:23:44,520
'Bye, Dad. I'll miss you.

394
00:23:46,689 --> 00:23:48,520
Thanks. I needed that.

395
00:23:50,649 --> 00:23:53,004
I'll be back in 137 hours.

396
00:23:54,609 --> 00:23:55,883
Have fun!

397
00:24:02,209 --> 00:24:03,642
Not too much.

398
00:24:21,049 --> 00:24:24,803
<i>It's hard to believe that</i>
<i>my mother's whole life fits into this box.</i>

399
00:24:25,129 --> 00:24:29,202
<i>I've just got to think of this stuff as clues.</i>
<i>Or good-luck charms.</i>

400
00:24:30,449 --> 00:24:32,679
<i>But I need more than luck</i>
<i>to solve this puzzle.</i>

401
00:24:33,409 --> 00:24:34,637
<i>I need a miracle.</i>

402
00:24:57,889 --> 00:25:01,928
<i>Arriving passengers, Flight 57,</i>
<i>your baggage is now available...</i>

403
00:25:02,009 --> 00:25:03,601
<i>... on Carousel 2.</i>

404
00:25:14,129 --> 00:25:16,962
<i>Arriving passengers</i>
<i>please go to ticket agent...</i>

405
00:25:17,049 --> 00:25:19,324
<i>... at the airline's reservation counter.</i>

406
00:25:44,009 --> 00:25:46,159
Are you waiting for someone?

407
00:25:47,409 --> 00:25:49,161
Excuse me, I asked you a question.

408
00:25:49,249 --> 00:25:52,082
I'm not suppose to talk to strangers,
not even nuns.

409
00:25:52,169 --> 00:25:53,887
You're Vada, right?

410
00:25:55,049 --> 00:25:57,643
- How did you know my name?
- Your Uncle Phil told me.

411
00:25:57,729 --> 00:25:59,481
Where is he?
He was supposed to meet me.

412
00:25:59,569 --> 00:26:02,561
Hey, relax!
You think I kidnapped him or something?

413
00:26:02,849 --> 00:26:04,885
This is California. Anything's possible.

414
00:26:05,169 --> 00:26:08,605
Well, if I was looking for a victim,
I wouldn't pick your Uncle Phil...

415
00:26:08,689 --> 00:26:11,328
...who outweighs me by about 150 pounds.

416
00:26:11,409 --> 00:26:14,765
Besides, who would I ask for ransom?
You?

417
00:26:15,249 --> 00:26:19,037
Are you suffering from a chemical
imbalance or is it just an attitude problem?

418
00:26:19,209 --> 00:26:22,485
My only problem is that your uncle's
given me $5 to pick you up...

419
00:26:22,569 --> 00:26:24,605
...but I don't get paid till delivery.

420
00:26:24,689 --> 00:26:26,407
Gee, that is a problem.

421
00:26:29,769 --> 00:26:31,600
Put that down! I'll call the police!

422
00:26:32,529 --> 00:26:36,283
What are you gonna do? Tell them that
a polite person helped carry your bag?

423
00:26:36,729 --> 00:26:37,878
You're not very polite.

424
00:26:37,969 --> 00:26:42,485
I don't think you're very grateful.
A lot of people would say thank you.

425
00:26:44,569 --> 00:26:46,560
- Thank you.
- Don't mention it.

426
00:26:47,169 --> 00:26:50,764
- I don't even know your name.
- It's Nick. There you go.

427
00:26:52,849 --> 00:26:54,680
- Okay.
- Thanks.

428
00:26:56,449 --> 00:26:58,201
Oh, great! No cabs.

429
00:26:58,289 --> 00:26:59,517
I have a gift for you.

430
00:26:59,609 --> 00:27:01,486
- Thanks.
- No, thanks.

431
00:27:02,009 --> 00:27:04,728
- He said it was a gift.
- Yeah, right.

432
00:27:04,809 --> 00:27:07,687
- Look, I don't need you to be telling me to...
- Taxi!

433
00:27:08,529 --> 00:27:09,678
Get in. Get in!

434
00:27:13,329 --> 00:27:16,207
You look like you know where to go.
Where are we headed?

435
00:27:16,289 --> 00:27:19,599
Take the 405 to Santa Monica,
then to Whittier to Sunset.

436
00:28:32,009 --> 00:28:34,728
Here you go. See that building?

437
00:28:35,089 --> 00:28:38,843
My grandfather built it.
Budapest Auto Repair.

438
00:28:39,769 --> 00:28:42,044
That's my room, right up there.

439
00:28:42,769 --> 00:28:45,727
One of these days,
this is all gonna be mine.

440
00:28:49,929 --> 00:28:51,282
Uncle Phil!

441
00:28:52,569 --> 00:28:53,684
Vada!

442
00:28:55,489 --> 00:28:56,922
Look at you!

443
00:28:57,049 --> 00:29:00,280
Hi! Hi, honey! How are you?

444
00:29:00,489 --> 00:29:03,640
- You look great! How's Shelly? Your dad?
- They're great.

445
00:29:03,729 --> 00:29:05,924
How about Nick?
Did he take good care of you?

446
00:29:06,009 --> 00:29:08,603
He was very polite. Worth the entire $5.

447
00:29:09,569 --> 00:29:11,287
Well, good to know.

448
00:29:13,089 --> 00:29:14,283
Thanks.

449
00:29:14,849 --> 00:29:16,760
Give it back, Nicholas.

450
00:29:17,049 --> 00:29:18,846
But we made a business deal!

451
00:29:19,129 --> 00:29:22,246
Whatever happened
to a good-old-fashioned favour?

452
00:29:23,049 --> 00:29:25,358
Our family's been dealing
with your company...

453
00:29:25,449 --> 00:29:29,328
...for over 40 years. Either the chain
is here or it isn't, and I don't see it.

454
00:29:29,409 --> 00:29:31,320
You wanna come down and explain why...

455
00:29:31,409 --> 00:29:33,969
...we can't fix cars 'cause parts aren't here?
Come on.

456
00:29:34,049 --> 00:29:36,722
I already have weight trouble.
I don't need your blubber.

457
00:29:36,809 --> 00:29:39,801
Are we clear on this,
or do I have to speak with your father?

458
00:29:40,929 --> 00:29:42,157
Thank you.

459
00:29:43,449 --> 00:29:45,519
Yes, yes, I love you too, Irving.

460
00:29:47,849 --> 00:29:49,680
You must be Vada!

461
00:29:50,009 --> 00:29:52,762
Oh, what a face!

462
00:29:53,529 --> 00:29:56,965
Oh, if I had a face like that,
I wouldn't have to yell so much.

463
00:29:57,809 --> 00:30:01,165
I'm Rose. Rose Zsigmond.
Nick's mother, among other things.

464
00:30:01,249 --> 00:30:02,523
You're Nick's mother?

465
00:30:02,769 --> 00:30:05,237
Did you think he was raised
by a pack of wolves?

466
00:30:05,329 --> 00:30:06,967
Don't be misled by the haircut.

467
00:30:07,049 --> 00:30:08,084
Mum!

468
00:30:08,169 --> 00:30:11,525
Who knew when I started working
in the finest foreign car shop in LA...

469
00:30:11,769 --> 00:30:13,600
...I'd also find the light of my life?

470
00:30:13,689 --> 00:30:15,441
Well, he left out a couple of steps.

471
00:30:15,529 --> 00:30:17,281
I've gotta get back to these bills.

472
00:30:17,369 --> 00:30:18,848
Will you help Vada get settled?

473
00:30:19,449 --> 00:30:21,804
Come on.
I'll show you where you're gonna stay.

474
00:30:24,889 --> 00:30:26,288
Here we go.

475
00:30:27,409 --> 00:30:29,718
Not what you expected
