00:45:29,809 --> 00:45:32,926
But, well, of course he'll remember.
Who could forget Maggie?

716
00:45:33,089 --> 00:45:34,363
Just one more thing.

717
00:45:35,129 --> 00:45:36,801
Does this mean anything to you?

718
00:45:39,129 --> 00:45:41,643
No, it doesn't, but I wish it did.

719
00:45:42,369 --> 00:45:45,088
Well, thanks for your help, Mr. Rosenfeld.

720
00:45:45,249 --> 00:45:47,558
I'm sorry my mother
wouldn't go out with you.

721
00:45:47,649 --> 00:45:49,799
I'm sure she would've had a great time.

722
00:45:49,889 --> 00:45:52,039
I would've tried to show her a good time.

723
00:45:52,129 --> 00:45:55,360
I promised her that I'd never forget her
and I never did.

724
00:45:56,249 --> 00:45:58,683
Stanley Rosenfeld does not forget.

725
00:46:02,249 --> 00:46:04,888
This is the street he walks down every day.

726
00:46:04,969 --> 00:46:08,757
- When he needs inspiration...
- Boy, you're really into this.

727
00:46:09,329 --> 00:46:11,206
He is one of the great poets.

728
00:46:16,369 --> 00:46:17,404
I think it's him.

729
00:46:27,289 --> 00:46:28,688
He's writing.

730
00:46:34,169 --> 00:46:35,318
Hello?

731
00:46:36,529 --> 00:46:40,363
If you're selling Girl Scout cookies,
I'm borderline diabetic.

732
00:46:41,529 --> 00:46:43,485
You're Alfred Beidermeyer, aren't you?

733
00:46:43,969 --> 00:46:45,766
You had to remind me?

734
00:46:46,529 --> 00:46:50,044
- Are you writing a poem?
- No, I'm writing the phone company...

735
00:46:50,409 --> 00:46:54,004
...because they keep charging me
for calls to Caracas, Venezuela.

736
00:46:54,089 --> 00:46:56,887
Do you know anybody
in Caracas, Venezuela?

737
00:46:57,649 --> 00:46:58,684
No.

738
00:46:58,889 --> 00:47:00,322
Neither do I.

739
00:47:01,969 --> 00:47:04,437
"Ask not for whom the bell tolls."

740
00:47:04,969 --> 00:47:07,767
Time for my medication and my nap.

741
00:47:10,449 --> 00:47:14,442
- Here, we'll help you carry this stuff.
- I can handle that.

742
00:47:16,169 --> 00:47:18,922
Oh, thank you. I'm in the penthouse.

743
00:47:25,009 --> 00:47:28,718
Penthouse A. It's there, over on the left.

744
00:47:38,569 --> 00:47:42,198
If he has a heart attack,
you're carrying the body down yourself.

745
00:47:47,809 --> 00:47:51,597
- At least it gives you plenty of exercise.
- It keeps me young.

746
00:48:00,369 --> 00:48:03,805
- Where do you want this?
- Just put it over there.

747
00:48:08,449 --> 00:48:10,758
- Do you still teach?
- No, no, no.

748
00:48:10,889 --> 00:48:12,959
I gave it up 10 years ago.

749
00:48:13,689 --> 00:48:15,327
Actually, it gave me up.

750
00:48:15,529 --> 00:48:18,089
My mother took this course with you
at UCLA.

751
00:48:18,289 --> 00:48:20,041
"Foundations of Poetic Thought."

752
00:48:20,129 --> 00:48:23,644
UCLA? My cardigan sweater period.

753
00:48:24,049 --> 00:48:25,926
Her name was Maggie Muldovan.

754
00:48:26,129 --> 00:48:27,164
Oh.

755
00:48:27,529 --> 00:48:28,803
Remember her?

756
00:48:29,089 --> 00:48:31,557
I've been blessed with a very bad memory.

757
00:48:31,809 --> 00:48:34,039
People say she looked like me.

758
00:48:35,489 --> 00:48:38,322
I was drinking a little in those days.

759
00:48:39,369 --> 00:48:41,963
I'm drinking a little these days, too.

760
00:48:42,729 --> 00:48:45,084
I'm sure she found
your lectures fascinating.

761
00:48:45,169 --> 00:48:46,682
Oh, I doubt it.

762
00:48:48,369 --> 00:48:51,042
Writers are notoriously boring.

763
00:48:51,129 --> 00:48:52,721
No, they're not.

764
00:48:53,009 --> 00:48:54,761
I don't wanna be a writer.

765
00:48:55,169 --> 00:48:57,160
I wanna be just like you.

766
00:49:00,729 --> 00:49:01,764
Me?

767
00:49:02,089 --> 00:49:06,321
My dear, this is not a country
that rewards poetry.

768
00:49:06,769 --> 00:49:09,602
This is a country that rewards gas mileage.

769
00:49:10,329 --> 00:49:14,720
Besides, people don't read poetry anymore,
they watch television.

770
00:49:16,049 --> 00:49:17,641
Don't be a poet.

771
00:49:18,089 --> 00:49:20,239
Be a TV repairman!

772
00:49:39,329 --> 00:49:40,808
Vada, come on.

773
00:49:41,809 --> 00:49:44,801
I've got a place I always go
when I need cheering up.

774
00:49:49,529 --> 00:49:52,805
The tar pits?
This is where you come to get cheered up?

775
00:49:52,889 --> 00:49:54,322
Look at it this way:

776
00:49:54,409 --> 00:49:57,481
However bad I feel,
it isn't as bad as becoming extinct...

777
00:49:57,569 --> 00:49:59,639
...in a bottomless pit of tar.

778
00:50:00,169 --> 00:50:02,205
And I thought I was weird.

779
00:50:02,569 --> 00:50:03,888
You are weird.

780
00:50:05,809 --> 00:50:07,242
Let's just go.

781
00:50:07,369 --> 00:50:10,167
Oh, no. Wait.
I like that you brought me here.

782
00:50:11,329 --> 00:50:15,322
Hey, what do I care?
I mean, consider the source:

783
00:50:15,649 --> 00:50:18,800
A chick from Pennsylvania
who wears a mood ring.

784
00:50:19,369 --> 00:50:21,007
This isn't just a mood ring.

785
00:50:22,089 --> 00:50:23,522
Does it work?

786
00:50:24,529 --> 00:50:26,918
Well, it doesn't open cans or anything...

787
00:50:28,329 --> 00:50:31,605
It's sort of a reminder of a friend of mine.

788
00:50:33,129 --> 00:50:34,448
Boyfriend?

789
00:50:34,929 --> 00:50:37,602
Well, he was a boy. He was my friend.

790
00:50:38,969 --> 00:50:40,925
He was my best friend.

791
00:50:43,249 --> 00:50:45,001
When we were kids we were gonna...

792
00:50:45,089 --> 00:50:47,728
...move out here and live
with the Brady Bunch.

793
00:50:51,809 --> 00:50:54,482
Then, I lost this ring in the woods...

794
00:50:56,209 --> 00:51:01,078
...and when he went to find it,
he got stung by bees and he died.

795
00:51:05,329 --> 00:51:07,638
Do you think your friend's
up in heaven now...

796
00:51:07,969 --> 00:51:10,688
...Iooking down on you,
and watching you all the time?

797
00:51:12,849 --> 00:51:16,000
Well, I hope he's not watching me
all the time.

798
00:51:21,769 --> 00:51:23,805
Let me see if it changes colours on me.

799
00:51:24,569 --> 00:51:25,524
Okay.

800
00:51:26,609 --> 00:51:30,124
But be careful.
It has a lot of sentimental value.

801
00:51:31,969 --> 00:51:34,005
Maybe it'll fit my pinkie.

802
00:51:34,689 --> 00:51:36,725
Well, don't force it. You'll break it.

803
00:51:36,809 --> 00:51:39,607
I'm not gonna break it.
I just wanna see it change colours.

804
00:51:39,929 --> 00:51:42,602
I want it back now.
I never should have taken it off.

805
00:51:42,689 --> 00:51:45,283
- I want it back.
- Hey, relax! I'm not gonna break it!

806
00:51:45,369 --> 00:51:47,007
- Give it to me.
- Come and get it.

807
00:51:47,089 --> 00:51:48,966
- Just give it to me!
- It's right here.

808
00:51:49,049 --> 00:51:50,277
Just come and get it.

809
00:51:50,369 --> 00:51:52,121
- Right here.
- Don't! Come on.

810
00:51:52,209 --> 00:51:53,608
Watch it.

811
00:51:53,729 --> 00:51:55,208
Don't!

812
00:51:57,089 --> 00:51:58,238
Uh-oh.

813
00:51:59,649 --> 00:52:01,685
What do you mean, "uh-oh"?

814
00:52:03,169 --> 00:52:04,602
I dropped it.

815
00:52:04,969 --> 00:52:06,322
In the tar?

816
00:52:07,689 --> 00:52:10,328
It was an accident. I'll get you a new one.

817
00:52:11,409 --> 00:52:13,161
Where are you going?

818
00:52:14,809 --> 00:52:16,959
Vada, wait up! Wait!

819
00:52:21,729 --> 00:52:24,687
- What are you doing? You can't go in.
- Oh, no?

820
00:52:25,009 --> 00:52:27,398
- It's dangerous!
- Leave me alone.

821
00:52:29,769 --> 00:52:33,205
That ring is the only thing
I have left of Thomas J. I have to get it.

822
00:52:33,529 --> 00:52:35,247
You mean this ring?

823
00:52:40,129 --> 00:52:42,085
You jerk! You idiot!

824
00:52:42,569 --> 00:52:44,878
You hit pretty good, for a girl!

825
00:53:13,089 --> 00:53:14,363
Nicholas!

826
00:53:15,169 --> 00:53:17,000
What are you doing up?

827
00:53:19,889 --> 00:53:21,447
I'm thirsty.

828
00:53:21,529 --> 00:53:23,520
There's water in your bathroom.

829
00:53:23,609 --> 00:53:25,042
I want juice.

830
00:53:25,409 --> 00:53:28,128
- Don't wake up Vada.
- I won't.

831
00:53:41,569 --> 00:53:43,958
I think Maggie could've been
a major player.

832
00:53:44,049 --> 00:53:45,402
She had the talent.

833
00:53:45,609 --> 00:53:48,169
God knows that face was made
for close-ups.

834
00:53:48,249 --> 00:53:50,922
And everything was magic with Maggie.

835
00:53:51,009 --> 00:53:54,240
I remember we were walking down
Hollywood Boulevard one night...

836
00:53:54,329 --> 00:53:56,638
...and we put our feet
in the stars' footprints.

837
00:53:56,729 --> 00:53:59,880
You know, like tourists do?
Maggie could not believe it.

838
00:53:59,969 --> 00:54:02,278
Her feet were the same size
as Judy Garland.

839
00:54:02,609 --> 00:54:05,169
'Course, mine matched perfectly
with Orson Welles.

840
00:54:05,649 --> 00:54:06,684
Just kidding.

841
00:54:09,129 --> 00:54:11,518
You should call Hillary Mitchell.

842
00:54:11,889 --> 00:54:13,845
She and Maggie were very close.

843
00:54:14,009 --> 00:54:17,160
She's got this funky little clothing store
over here on Melrose.

844
00:54:17,249 --> 00:54:20,605
I'd call her for you, but, well,
we kinda had this thing...

845
00:54:20,689 --> 00:54:23,761
...you know, and it got a little messy.

846
00:54:25,129 --> 00:54:26,244
Thanks.

847
00:54:28,249 --> 00:54:30,399
Would you know what this is?

848
00:54:30,489 --> 00:54:31,717
Well, not really.

849
00:54:31,929 --> 00:54:36,684
Could be the date of an opening,
an audition, birthday?

850
00:54:37,169 --> 00:54:39,046
Not my birthday. I don't know.

851
00:54:39,129 --> 00:54:41,518
Who writes dates on paper bags?

852
00:54:41,809 --> 00:54:43,003
My mum.

853
00:54:43,169 --> 00:54:46,684
Whoa! I have got to get to dailies.
I gotta break this up.

854
00:54:46,769 --> 00:54:49,408
Well, thanks for your time.
I know you're very busy.

855
00:54:49,489 --> 00:54:51,719
You are Maggie all over again.

856
00:54:52,489 --> 00:54:55,083
You let me know
if you ever want to be a movie star.

857
00:54:55,569 --> 00:54:57,719
You got the face for close-ups, too.

858
00:54:57,809 --> 00:54:59,003
Thanks.

859
00:55:06,129 --> 00:55:07,562
What a dufus.

860
00:55:14,049 --> 00:55:17,724
We may go for coffee after the meeting,
so don't expect us before midnight.

861
00:55:17,809 --> 00:55:20,323
- There's fruit.
- You know where the extinguisher is.

862
00:55:20,409 --> 00:55:22,969
If the fruit bursts into flames,
I'll be prepared.

863
00:55:23,209 --> 00:55:24,847
You're so clever.

864
00:55:25,969 --> 00:55:28,437
- Are you all right, honey?
- I'm just tired.

865
00:55:28,569 --> 00:55:31,003
Well, get to bed early
and don't let anybody in.

866
00:55:31,089 --> 00:55:33,284
- 'Bye.
- Lock the door.

867
00:55:47,889 --> 00:55:49,880
We have lift-off.

868
00:55:51,289 --> 00:55:53,757
Joan Crawford! Oh, I love her.

869
00:55:53,849 --> 00:55:55,567
There's the Marx Brothers!

870
00:55:57,009 --> 00:56:01,241
- Carole Lombard! My dad's favourite.
- Never heard of her.

871
00:56:01,609 --> 00:56:04,123
Montgomery Clift! Wait till I tell Shelly.

872
00:56:04,369 --> 00:56:06,121
Here's Judy Garland!

873
00:56:11,129 --> 00:56:15,884
- My mother stood on this very spot.
- I'm afraid your feet won't fit there.

874
00:56:18,969 --> 00:56:22,200
That's 'cause I was cursed
with the Sultenfuss bear claws.

875
00:56:24,609 --> 00:56:26,759
- My hands fit.
- Big deal.

876
00:56:32,169 --> 00:56:33,397
What's he smoking?

877
00:56:33,529 --> 00:56:35,201
What do you think?

878
00:56:35,929 --> 00:56:37,123
Really?

879
00:56:45,409 --> 00:56:46,728
Hey, look.

880
00:56:55,449 --> 00:56:57,883
This is a totally barbaric custom.

881
00:57:01,129 --> 00:57:04,280
So, if Phil marries my mum,
she'd be your aunt, right?

882
00:57:04,969 --> 00:57:06,084
Right.

883
00:57:06,409 --> 00:57:07,922
And you'd be my cousin?

884
00:57:09,289 --> 00:57:11,928
Yeah, I guess. Sort of.

885
00:57:12,969 --> 00:57:15,767
But we wouldn't really be related, right?

886
00:57:16,129 --> 00:57:19,201
Oh, no, we wouldn't be
from the same bloodlines or anything.

887
00:57:19,689 --> 00:57:23,967
We'd be like two total strangers
who accidentally had relatives...

888
00:57:24,049 --> 00:57:25,528
...who got married.

889
00:57:25,929 --> 00:57:27,806
Good. I mean...

890
00:57:29,289 --> 00:57:31,598
Marriage can really complicate things.

891
00:57:34,969 --> 00:57:38,245
So, aren't you gonna say anything
about my earrings?

892
00:57:38,769 --> 00:57:40,168
I already did.

893
00:57:40,249 --> 00:57:42,365
It's a totally barbaric custom.

894
00:57:43,249 --> 00:57:44,523
But on you...

895
00:57:45,889 --> 00:57:47,288
...it looks good.

896
00:58:05,929 --> 00:58:08,284
- We should've called.
- It's not that late.

897
00:58:18,849 --> 00:58:20,805
You're grounded till you're 50.

898
00:58:20,889 --> 00:58:23,198
- You're overreacting.
- Make that 60.

899
00:58:23,329 --> 00:58:25,479
And I'm docking your allowance
for two weeks.

900
00:58:25,569 --> 00:58:27,446
- Mum!
- You think this is easy for me?

901
00:58:27,529 --> 00:58:29,884
You go out and I get to be the bad guy.

902
00:58:30,089 --> 00:58:31,761
I don't want you to be a delinquent...

903
00:58:31,849 --> 00:58:34,409
...but I can't do my job
if you don't do yours.

904
00:58:34,489 --> 00:58:37,322
- It's not his fault.
- No. It was me.

905
00:58:38,089 --> 00:58:39,727
I'm sorry, Mum. Really.

906
00:58:39,809 --> 00:58:42,369
Just tell me what to do. I'll do anything.

907
00:58:42,769 --> 00:58:43,963
Go to your room.

908
00:58:46,129 --> 00:58:47,198
And you.

909
00:58:47,449 --> 00:58:50,680
Your father didn't give you permission
to pierce your ears, did he?

910
00:58:50,769 --> 00:58:52,168
Not exactly.

911
00:58:53,329 --> 00:58:55,399
Well, just don't shave your legs.

912
00:58:55,569 --> 00:58:59,482
He'll never let you visit us again if I send
you home hairless and full of holes.

913
00:59:21,569 --> 00:59:24,037
- Good morning.
- Well, maybe for you.

914
00:59:24,249 --> 00:59:26,001
- Is something wrong?
- You're lucky...

915
00:59:26,089 --> 00:59:28,478
...you deal with kids
who are under anaesthesia.

916
00:59:29,449 --> 00:59:33,362
Well, even without anaesthesia,
I always tell my patients to...

917
00:59:34,969 --> 00:59:36,118
...relax.

918
00:59:37,329 --> 00:59:39,889
Isn't it time for your coffee break
or something?

919
00:59:39,969 --> 00:59:42,403
There must be someplace
where we can go, talk.

920
00:59:42,489 --> 00:59:44,400
Oh, no, I couldn't.

921
00:59:44,809 --> 00:59:46,128
You couldn't?

922
00:59:46,209 --> 00:59:48,006
Well, I'm sort of involved.

923
00:59:48,329 --> 00:59:51,799
- Sort of?
- Let's just say I'm involved.

924
00:59:52,769 --> 00:59:55,044
Where I come from, involvement calls for...

925
00:59:55,129 --> 00:59:56,960
...a substantial piece of jewellery.

926
00:59:57,049 --> 00:59:59,609
Oh, well, I don't wear a lot of jewellery.

927
01:00:00,689 --> 01:00:04,079
Alright, so you don't like jewellery,
but you do like good music.

928
01:00:04,329 --> 01:00:06,445
Liszt. One of my favourites.

929
01:00:08,089 --> 01:00:10,649
Liszt was my parents' favourite.
They were Hungarian.

930
01:00:10,729 --> 01:00:13,687
Hungarians.
Famous for their beautiful music...

931
01:00:14,969 --> 01:00:16,641
...their beautiful women.

932
01:00:16,729 --> 01:00:19,243
Doctor Helburn! What a surprise.

933
01:00:19,809 --> 01:00:23,643
In the last couple of days, we've changed
your oil, relined your brakes...

934
01:00:23,809 --> 01:00:26,960
...balanced and rotated your tyres,
aligned your front-end...

935
01:00:27,129 --> 01:00:29,324
...and flushed out
your entire cooling system.

936
01:00:29,409 --> 01:00:32,401
I really didn't expect to be seeing you
for another 3000 miles.

937
01:00:32,489 --> 01:00:35,845
Well, what can I say, Phil?
It's just I feel so welcome here.

938
01:00:35,929 --> 01:00:37,123
And you are.

939
01:00:41,489 --> 01:00:43,320
Why don't I come in the morning?

940
01:00:43,409 --> 01:00:45,764
You can check out that left blinker for me.

941
01:00:46,089 --> 01:00:47,602
Oh, sure. Okay.

942
01:00:48,569 --> 01:00:50,844
I'll see you then. I look forward to it.

943
01:01:03,369 --> 01:01:06,998
We really ought to flush out
that line of bullshit he's got.

944
01:01:07,729 --> 01:01:10,926
"Hungarians are famous
for their beautiful women."

945
01:01:11,089 --> 01:01:15,207
What's wrong with a little flattery?
What's wrong with a little appreciation?

946
01:01:15,289 --> 01:01:17,120
Are you saying I don't appreciate?

947
01:01:17,209 --> 01:01:20,042
I'm saying he asked me out for coffee,
like a real date.

948
01:01:20,329 --> 01:01:22,160
When was the last time you did that?

949
01:01:22,249 --> 01:01:24,319
What do you mean?
We have a date every night.

950
01:01:24,409 --> 01:01:27,640
No, that's not a date.
A date is when I don't cook.

951
01:01:30,249 --> 01:01:32,001
I do the dishes.

952
01:01:36,009 --> 01:01:39,524
<i>I'd go to a fortune teller,</i>
<i>but they can only predict the future.</i>

953
01:01:40,889 --> 01:01:43,403
<i>I need someone who can predict the past.</i>

954
01:01:51,769 --> 01:01:54,886
Hi. Can I help you?

955
01:01:55,769 --> 01:01:59,159
Are you the Hillary Mitchell who went
to school with Maggie Muldovan?

956
01:01:59,249 --> 01:02:00,887
Maggie Muldovan?

957
01:02:01,849 --> 01:02:03,567
Did you know her?

958
01:02:03,809 --> 01:02:05,481
She's her daughter, Vada.

959
01:02:06,969 --> 01:02:08,448
Of course!

960
01:02:10,209 --> 01:02:11,608
Look at you.

961
01:02:11,809 --> 01:02:15,643
It's the eyes mostly, and the hair, too.

962
01:02:17,049 --> 01:02:18,801
And now she's gone.

963
01:02:19,289 --> 01:02:20,244
She's gone.

964
01:02:21,009 --> 01:02:24,285
She'll never get to see
how well you've turned out.

965
01:02:26,689 --> 01:02:28,008
Oh, my God!

966
01:02:29,129 --> 01:02:30,448
Maggie!

967
01:02:31,289 --> 01:02:32,961
You poor thing.

968
01:02:34,529 --> 01:02:37,123
It's okay, really. I was just a baby.

969
01:02:40,249 --> 01:02:42,001
I'm sorry. It's just...

970
01:02:43,369 --> 01:02:46,918
...I've been taking all these seminars
to get in touch with my feelings...

971
01:02:47,089 --> 01:02:49,649
...and sometimes it gets outta hand.

972
01:02:51,169 --> 01:02:52,158
Here.

973
01:02:52,769 --> 01:02:55,442
Thank you. You're very sweet.

974
01:02:58,609 --> 01:03:00,679
How did you find out where I was?

975
01:03:01,089 --> 01:03:02,408
Peter Webb told us.

976
01:03:03,609 --> 01:03:04,644
Peter?

977
01:03:05,649 --> 01:03:06,877
You saw Peter?

978
01:03:08,209 --> 01:03:09,437
Oh, God.

979
01:03:20,489 --> 01:03:24,118
Forgive me. I'm making such a scene here.

980
01:03:24,929 --> 01:03:27,045
- Why don't you have a seat?
- Thanks.

981
01:03:27,409 --> 01:03:30,481
I remember Maggie and your dad, too.

982
01:03:30,849 --> 01:03:35,400
You know, we used to all pile
into his old '54 Ford pickup.

983
01:03:36,289 --> 01:03:38,644
"Chuck the truck" we used to call it.

984
01:03:39,289 --> 01:03:42,520
It was pitch black with red leather interior.

985
01:03:43,329 --> 01:03:45,320
Does he still drive that?

986
01:03:45,489 --> 01:03:48,287
No, but sometimes he drives a hearse.

987
01:03:49,649 --> 01:03:51,367
He's an undertaker.

988
01:03:51,529 --> 01:03:53,042
You're kidding.

989
01:03:53,369 --> 01:03:55,724
Jeffrey Pommeroy's an undertaker?

990
01:03:58,529 --> 01:04:00,679
His name's Harry Sultenfuss.

991
01:04:06,409 --> 01:04:08,127
What are you saying?

992
01:04:09,649 --> 01:04:11,048
Look, I...

993
01:04:11,609 --> 01:04:14,077
Are you saying my mum
had another husband?

994
01:04:14,169 --> 01:04:18,242
Honey, back then, people did crazy things.

995
01:04:18,769 --> 01:04:19,963
They sure did!

996
01:04:20,049 --> 01:04:23,200
They got kicked outta school,
they married truck drivers.

997
01:04:23,809 --> 01:04:26,243
These are my mother's
greatest accomplishments?

998
01:04:26,329 --> 01:04:29,401
I'm sure glad I came all the way out here
to find them out.

999
01:04:38,849 --> 01:04:39,998
Vada, wait up!

1000
01:04:41,209 --> 01:04:45,725
Just 'cause your mum was married before,
doesn't mean anything.

1001
01:04:47,169 --> 01:04:49,637
Maybe not. But maybe it does.

1002
01:04:51,369 --> 01:04:53,564
If no one told me about this...

1003
01:04:53,809 --> 01:04:56,118
Maybe they're trying to hide something.

1004
01:04:56,569 --> 01:04:57,888
Like what?

1005
01:04:59,049 --> 01:05:01,927
Maybe this Jeffrey guy is my real father.

1006
01:05:05,089 --> 01:05:06,283
Look at me.

1007
01:05:06,689 --> 01:05:09,522
I have the hair of a dead person,
and my nose...

1008
01:05:10,809 --> 01:05:12,959
No one in my family has this nose.

1009
01:05:13,649 --> 01:05:16,527
It could be the nose
of a complete stranger.

1010
01:05:18,009 --> 01:05:21,319
I came out here to find out
about my mother and I found...

1011
01:05:22,289 --> 01:05:23,278
God.

1012
01:05:24,649 --> 01:05:25,843
Don't cry.

1013
01:05:27,009 --> 01:05:28,078
Come on.

1014
01:05:29,129 --> 01:05:31,723
That lady in there
looked pretty flaky to me.

1015
01:05:33,169 --> 01:05:36,479
How bout Phil?
Maybe he knows something about all this.

1016
01:05:36,649 --> 01:05:39,846
At least you should talk to him
before you get worked up.

1017
01:05:41,609 --> 01:05:43,440
Before I get worked up?

1018
01:05:45,009 --> 01:05:47,318
You don't think this is worked up?

1019
01:05:55,129 --> 01:05:57,279
That thing you said about your nose?

1020
01:05:58,369 --> 01:06:00,087
That it was a stranger's nose?

1021
01:06:00,809 --> 01:06:02,322
It's not. It's...

1022
01:06:02,809 --> 01:06:04,083
I mean...

1023
01:06:04,849 --> 01:06:06,362
It's yours.

1024
01:06:10,329 --> 01:06:11,444
Nick?

1025
01:06:12,289 --> 01:06:13,404
Yeah?

1026
01:06:15,169 --> 01:06:17,637
This has been a real confusing day.

1027
01:06:22,129 --> 01:06:25,007
How could Dad let me visit here
and find out like this?

1028
01:06:29,409 --> 01:06:32,287
I'm gonna call him
and make him tell me everything.

1029
01:06:33,449 --> 01:06:34,677
Sweetie, I...

1030
01:06:34,929 --> 01:06:37,887
Don't worry,
I'll do it in my own subtle way.

1031
01:06:44,049 --> 01:06:45,721
<i>Hello, Sultenfuss Parlour.</i>

1032
01:06:45,809 --> 01:06:47,720
- Hi, Dad.
<i>- Hi, honey!</i>

1033
01:06:47,929 --> 01:06:50,841
I just called to say
that I'm having a really great time.

1034
01:06:51,049 --> 01:06:54,359
<i>Good. You should go over</i>
<i>and watch them tape Carson.</i>

1035
01:06:55,849 --> 01:06:59,319
Actually, I wanna see Jeffrey Pommeroy.

1036
01:07:00,689 --> 01:07:03,203
Is he some kind of a new rock star
or something?

1037
01:07:05,049 --> 01:07:06,004
Yeah.

1038
01:07:06,089 --> 01:07:07,442
<i>Totally groovy, huh?</i>

1039
01:07:07,649 --> 01:07:08,445
Totally.

1040
01:07:08,929 --> 01:07:10,806
Ask him if he needs a good tuba player.

1041
01:07:12,129 --> 01:07:13,198
I will.

1042
01:07:13,809 --> 01:07:15,003
How's Shelly?

1043
01:07:16,289 --> 01:07:17,278
She's fine.

1044
01:07:17,369 --> 01:07:21,282
The doctor just told her to stay in bed
and get a little rest...

1045
01:07:21,409 --> 01:07:23,877
...and stay quiet just to make sure that...

1046
01:07:24,809 --> 01:07:25,878
Okay.

1047
01:07:26,609 --> 01:07:28,281
'Bye, Daddy. I love you.

1048
01:07:28,769 --> 01:07:31,522
- I love you too, sweetie pie.
<i>- My love to Shelly.</i>

1049
01:07:38,049 --> 01:07:39,323
Shelly's sick.

1050
01:07:39,929 --> 01:07:43,205
I have to get to the bottom
of this whole thing and get back there.

1051
01:07:43,289 --> 01:07:44,847
She'll be all right, baby.

1052
01:07:44,929 --> 01:07:46,157
Yeah. Right.

1053
01:07:47,609 --> 01:07:49,679
It's pointless to worry.

1054
01:07:50,929 --> 01:07:53,887
I'm not authorised to trace licenses
for civilians.

1055
01:07:54,209 --> 01:07:57,804
His name is Jeffrey Pommeroy,
and he used to drive a '54 Ford pickup.

1056
01:07:57,889 --> 01:07:59,527
Black with red interior.

1057
01:08:00,569 --> 01:08:01,684
Please?

1058
01:08:02,449 --> 01:08:03,802
Give us a break.

1059
01:08:03,889 --> 01:08:06,278
All you have to do is make a phone call.

1060
01:08:07,689 --> 01:08:09,998
I thought I told you to lose this guy.

1061
01:08:10,089 --> 01:08:14,799
Sergeant, I know I said some things
last time that I shouldn't have said at all...

1062
01:08:14,889 --> 01:08:17,722
I think the phrase was "sleazoid geek."

1063
01:08:17,929 --> 01:08:19,487
I'm sorry, okay?

1064
01:08:19,569 --> 01:08:22,288
We gotta find this guy
because he knew Vada's mum...

1065
01:08:22,369 --> 01:08:25,327
...and he could tell her stuff
that no one else knows.

1066
01:08:25,409 --> 01:08:27,445
You're still asking me to break the law.

1067
01:08:27,529 --> 01:08:30,168
No, we're asking you to stand up
with Maggie Muldovan...

1068
01:08:30,249 --> 01:08:31,841
...like you should've years ago.

1069
01:08:41,769 --> 01:08:44,522
Yeah, this is Sergeant Tanaka
from Hollenbeck.

1070
01:08:45,089 --> 01:08:47,284
I need a current address for a Jeffrey...

1071
01:08:47,369 --> 01:08:48,358
Pommeroy.

1072
01:08:48,489 --> 01:08:49,524
Pommeroy.

1073
01:08:50,249 --> 01:08:53,207
He may or may not be driving
a black '54 Ford pickup.

1074
01:08:55,729 --> 01:08:56,923
Monday.

1075
01:08:57,089 --> 01:08:58,807
I'm leaving Sunday.

1076
01:09:00,489 --> 01:09:02,161
Could you hold on for a second?

1077
01:09:03,649 --> 01:09:06,766
I can't get priority
without a criminal charge.

1078
01:09:06,849 --> 01:09:09,488
Charge him with something.
Who's gonna know?

1079
01:09:09,849 --> 01:09:11,328
Me! I'll know.

1080
01:09:11,729 --> 01:09:13,924
Do you wanna be a hall monitor
all your life?

1081
01:09:18,729 --> 01:09:19,718
Hello.

1082
01:09:20,369 --> 01:09:22,564
I'm gonna need this right now.

1083
01:09:22,969 --> 01:09:24,038
This guy.

1084
01:09:25,369 --> 01:09:27,758
We think
he might be going after the governor.

1085
01:09:30,809 --> 01:09:33,004
Twenty minutes? Fine.

1086
01:09:39,049 --> 01:09:40,084
Give him a call.

1087
01:09:40,169 --> 01:09:42,478
The worst he can do
is hang up on you, right?

1088
01:09:42,969 --> 01:09:46,120
I feel like before I can talk to him,
I have to see his face.

1089
01:09:48,449 --> 01:09:50,485
How's this for a solution?

1090
01:09:51,609 --> 01:09:56,160
We'll take a drive over to his place.
You can introduce yourself...

1091
01:09:56,369 --> 01:09:58,166
I'd like to see his house, but...

1092
01:09:58,569 --> 01:10:02,608
...I don't know if I'd have the nerve
to just go up and knock on his door.

1093
01:10:03,649 --> 01:10:05,719
I don't think I could go through with it.

1094
01:10:05,809 --> 01:10:07,401
Then we'll keep driving.

1095
01:10:07,609 --> 01:10:08,928
You'll decide.

1096
01:10:19,569 --> 01:10:21,366
You're awfully quiet.

1097
01:10:23,609 --> 01:10:26,362
Do you think I should tell my dad
about Jeffrey Pommeroy?

1098
01:10:28,649 --> 01:10:31,607
I don't know. He's got an awful lot
on his mind right now.

1099
01:10:32,369 --> 01:10:34,599
Maybe some day when the time is right.

1100
01:10:36,049 --> 01:10:37,198
Maybe.

1101
01:10:38,129 --> 01:10:40,962
Then again,
your dad's got his own memories...

1102
01:10:41,049 --> 01:10:43,199
...and he's got his own life now.

1103
01:10:44,249 --> 01:10:47,764
I think this is a secret,
just between you and your mum.

1104
01:10:49,249 --> 01:10:51,604
A secret? I like that.

1105
01:11:21,529 --> 01:11:23,281
This is it, I guess.

1106
01:11:30,209 --> 01:11:33,804
Well, we've come this far,
the least I can do is knock on the door.

1107
01:11:35,609 --> 01:11:36,803
Want me to come with?

1108
01:11:38,169 --> 01:11:39,807
I should do this myself.

1109
01:11:39,969 --> 01:11:42,164
Okay. Take your time.

1110
01:11:42,369 --> 01:11:44,166
I'll go for a walk around.

1111
01:12:16,969 --> 01:12:19,005
Go ahead, honey. Go ahead.

1112
01:12:33,329 --> 01:12:34,603
Hi there.

1113
01:12:37,129 --> 01:12:38,244
Can I help you?

1114
01:12:39,569 --> 01:12:41,287
Are you Jeffrey Pommeroy?

1115
01:12:41,729 --> 01:12:43,640
I sure am. Who are you?

1116
01:12:46,169 --> 01:12:48,285
I'm Vada Margaret Sultenfuss.

1117
01:12:49,689 --> 01:12:51,520
- And my mother was...
- Maggie.

1118
01:12:52,209 --> 01:12:53,562
Maggie's little girl.

1119
01:12:56,849 --> 01:12:58,567
I was hoping I'd get to meet you.

1120
01:13:00,289 --> 01:13:02,359
You mean you knew about me?

1121
01:13:02,809 --> 01:13:04,083
Who is it, honey?

1122
01:13:04,169 --> 01:13:06,444
It's Maggie's little girl, Vada.

1123
01:13:07,329 --> 01:13:09,684
Oh. Oh, my.

1124
01:13:09,769 --> 01:13:11,600
- This is my wife, Emily.
- Hi.

1125
01:13:12,369 --> 01:13:13,404
Hi.

1126
01:13:15,849 --> 01:13:17,726
Can you come in for a minute?

1127
01:13:18,449 --> 01:13:20,201
I'd like to. Thanks.

1128
01:13:28,009 --> 01:13:29,203
Mummy! Daddy!

1129
01:13:29,329 --> 01:13:31,638
I painted you a rainbow. Come and see!

1130
01:13:32,049 --> 01:13:33,607
This is Vada.

1131
01:13:33,689 --> 01:13:35,884
Vada, this our little girl, Katie.

1132
01:13:36,049 --> 01:13:37,482
- Hi.
- Hi.

1133
01:13:40,329 --> 01:13:43,446
Why don't we let Daddy and Vada
visit for a little while, okay?

1134
01:13:43,529 --> 01:13:44,848
- Okay.
- Okay.

1135
01:13:45,969 --> 01:13:47,607
- 'Bye.
- 'Bye.

1136
01:13:50,849 --> 01:13:53,409
She looks a little like me
when I was a little girl.

1137
01:13:53,489 --> 01:13:54,365
Does she?

1138
01:13:57,049 --> 01:13:58,323
I'm glad you're here.

1139
01:13:58,609 --> 01:13:59,359
You are?

1140
01:13:59,849 --> 01:14:02,488
Yeah. Come on, let's talk.

1141
01:14:05,409 --> 01:14:08,481
We had an assignment
to write about someone we've never met...

1142
01:14:08,769 --> 01:14:09,804
...and I chose my mother.

1143
01:14:09,889 --> 01:14:13,165
She was born in LA,
and since my Uncle Phil moved out here...

1144
01:14:13,249 --> 01:14:16,446
...I came to visit him.
Then I looked in her high school yearbook...

1145
01:14:16,529 --> 01:14:19,726
...and I called a few people.
One guy said that she went to UCLA.

1146
01:14:19,809 --> 01:14:22,084
Another guy said
I should call Hillary Mitchell...

1147
01:14:22,169 --> 01:14:23,807
Hillary Mitchell? How's she?

1148
01:14:24,169 --> 01:14:25,363
She's great.

1149
01:14:25,449 --> 01:14:27,167
She's a little crazy, though.

1150
01:14:27,689 --> 01:14:29,964
Hillary said that you had
a black Ford truck...

1151
01:14:30,049 --> 01:14:33,359
...and this policeman I know
got in touch with Motor Vehicles...

1152
01:14:33,449 --> 01:14:36,009
...and he gave me your address
and here I am.

1153
01:14:37,729 --> 01:14:39,481
I told you it was a long story.

1154
01:14:39,569 --> 01:14:42,606
That's all right. You know,
you sounded just like your mother.

1155
01:14:42,689 --> 01:14:44,407
She told great stories.

1156
01:14:44,529 --> 01:14:47,805
Stories with crazy accents
and special effects.

1157
01:14:48,249 --> 01:14:49,364
Special effects?

1158
01:14:49,449 --> 01:14:52,885
Like switching the lamp on and off
when she was talking about lightning.

1159
01:14:53,169 --> 01:14:55,285
Audiences love stuff like that.

1160
01:14:55,369 --> 01:14:57,724
And your mum knew
how to work an audience.

1161
01:14:57,809 --> 01:14:59,686
I don't know very much about her.

1162
01:15:00,129 --> 01:15:01,926
I was hoping that you could help me.

1163
01:15:02,009 --> 01:15:02,885
I'll try.

1164
01:15:06,089 --> 01:15:08,159
No one else knows what this means.

1165
01:15:18,569 --> 01:15:21,925
The thing is we always wanted
to work in the theatre.

1166
01:15:23,169 --> 01:15:25,842
We drove out to New York, to Broadway...

1167
01:15:26,369 --> 01:15:28,963
...where it was all happening.

1168
01:15:29,849 --> 01:15:33,683
And New York was just full
of fancy French restaurants...

1169
01:15:33,769 --> 01:15:36,078
...and we wanted to get married in one.

1170
01:15:36,289 --> 01:15:38,325
But we were totally broke.

1171
01:15:38,729 --> 01:15:42,165
Your mum found this little coffee shop
with tables around the back...

1172
01:15:42,249 --> 01:15:46,003
...and real tablecloths on 'em,
and a minister who worked cheap.

1173
01:15:46,249 --> 01:15:48,285
When we got down to the coffee shop...

1174
01:15:48,369 --> 01:15:52,408
...there was a sign on the door that said,
"Closed by the Board of Health."

1175
01:15:52,489 --> 01:15:54,559
By that time, it had started snowing...

1176
01:15:54,649 --> 01:15:58,801
...so we just got married
right outside in the snow.

1177
01:16:00,449 --> 01:16:01,802
It was freezing.

1178
01:16:03,129 --> 01:16:04,642
But it was wonderful.

1179
01:16:06,449 --> 01:16:11,079
And for our wedding feast,
we had a bag of hot-roasted chestnuts.

1180
01:16:11,489 --> 01:16:12,808
This is the bag.

1181
01:16:14,609 --> 01:16:16,042
And she saved it.

1182
01:16:17,849 --> 01:16:19,487
We didn't have a camera.

1183
01:16:21,169 --> 01:16:23,637
So she just wrote the date
on the bag and said:

1184
01:16:23,729 --> 01:16:27,563
"This'll be our wedding album.
This'll be a day we'll never forget."

1185
01:16:29,729 --> 01:16:31,162
We never did.

1186
01:16:35,649 --> 01:16:37,640
Do you have any pictures of her?

1187
01:16:38,529 --> 01:16:40,565
I've got something better.

1188
01:16:47,009 --> 01:16:50,365
We called ourselves
"The Appearing Nightly Players."

1189
01:16:53,689 --> 01:16:56,408
<i>Darling! Where is my chauffeur?</i>

1190
01:16:56,569 --> 01:16:58,719
<i>You don't want I should walk to the stage?</i>

1191
01:16:58,809 --> 01:17:01,403
<i>An actress of my overwhelming talent!</i>

1192
01:17:08,649 --> 01:17:10,241
She's beautiful.

1193
01:17:19,009 --> 01:17:21,239
We performed on the beach one summer.

1194
01:17:22,329 --> 01:17:24,160
Everything went wrong.

1195
01:18:10,169 --> 01:18:12,729
<i>- Come on, send me away happy.</i>
<i>- Send him away!</i>

1196
01:19:45,889 --> 01:19:48,244
<i>- That was beautiful.</i>
<i>- Thank you.</i>

1197
01:19:48,969 --> 01:19:52,484
<i>- You do it all the time. That was beautiful.</i>
<i>- Thank you.</i>

1198
01:20:13,689 --> 01:20:15,725
She had a beautiful voice.

1199
01:20:21,729 --> 01:20:24,243
Would you like to have these movies?

1200
01:20:28,609 --> 01:20:30,520
More than anything in the world.

1201
01:20:32,449 --> 01:20:35,646
It's good to see Maggie again and you.

1202
01:20:38,449 --> 01:20:40,201
Didn't you ever wonder about me?

1203
01:20:40,289 --> 01:20:43,918
Well, I didn't know about you
until after she was gone.

1204
01:20:45,609 --> 01:20:50,000
I thought that maybe you'd be curious
about how I turned out.

1205
01:20:50,849 --> 01:20:52,601
I'd say you turned out just fine.

1206
01:20:52,689 --> 01:20:56,523
I guess what I mean is,
my mother married my dad after you.

1207
01:20:56,929 --> 01:21:00,763
And then I was born, so I thought that
maybe you got divorced because of me.

1208
01:21:00,849 --> 01:21:02,885
Wait a minute.

